-- 1. [Problem Restatement] Find the value of $(\log_2\frac{x}{y})^2$ given (i) $\log_2 x=\log_y 16$ and (ii) $xy=64$, for positive $x\neq1,\;y\neq1$. 2. [Key Idea] Rewrite everything in base 2: set $p=\log_2 x$ and $q=\log_2 y$; the two conditions then become simple equations in $p,q$ whose solution immediately yields $(p-q)^2$. 3. [Proof] Let p = log₂ x, q = log₂ y (so x = 2ᵖ, y = 2ᑫ). Condition (i): log_y 16 = log₂ x ⇔ 4 / log₂ y = p (using log_y a = log₂ a / log₂ y) ⇔ p q = 4. (1) Condition (ii): xy = 2ᵖ·2ᑫ = 2^{p+q} = 64 = 2⁶ ⇔ p + q = 6. (2) We want (log₂ (x/y))² = (p − q)². Using (1) and (2): (p − q)² = (p + q)² − 4pq = 6² − 4·4 = 36 − 16 = 20. 4. [Conclusion] Therefore $(\log_2\frac{x}{y})^2 = 20$, which is choice (B).
